</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Knowledge of right atrial anatomic and pathologic imaging findings and associated clinical symptoms is important to avoid false-positive diagnoses and missed findings. Complete evaluation of the heart often requires a multimodality approach that includes radiography, echocardiography, computed tomography (CT), magnetic resonance (MR) imaging, and invasive angiography. In general, CT provides the highest spatial resolution of these modalities at the cost of radiation exposure to the patient. Echocardiography and MR imaging offer complementary and detailed information for functional evaluation without added radiation exposure. The advantages and disadvantages of each modality for the evaluation of right atrial anatomic structure, size, and pathologic findings are discussed. Cardiac MR imaging is the reference standard for evaluation of right atrial size and volume but often is too time consuming and resource intensive to perform in routine clinical practice. Therefore, established reference ranges for two-dimensional transthoracic echocardiography are often used. Right atrial pathologic findings can be broadly categorized into <i>(a)</i> congenital anomalies (cor triatriatum dexter, Ebstein anomaly, and aneurysm), <i>(b)</i> disorders of volume (tricuspid regurgitation, pathologic mimics such as a pseudoaneurysm, and atrial septal defect), <i>(c)</i> disorders of pressure (tricuspid stenosis, restrictive cardiomyopathy, and constrictive pericarditis), and <i>(d)</i> masses (pseudomasses, thrombus, lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum, lipoma, myxoma, sarcoma, and metastatic disease). Familiarity with each pathologic entity and its treatment options is essential to ensure that appropriate imaging modalities are selected. <i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2015</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.351130010">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.351130010">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig1a.jpeg" height="879" width="650" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in an 86-year-old woman with arrhythmia. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram shows a questionable hyperechoic mass (arrow) in a normal-sized right atrium. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted electrocardiographically (<abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>) gated CT angiogram shows that the mass is a prominent crista terminalis (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig1b.jpeg" height="879" width="675" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in an 86-year-old woman with arrhythmia. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram shows a questionable hyperechoic mass (arrow) in a normal-sized right atrium. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted electrocardiographically (<abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>) gated CT angiogram shows that the mass is a prominent crista terminalis (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig2.jpeg" height="767" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Sagittal <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated coronary CT angiogram shows the eustachian valve (arrow) at the junction of the right atrium and inferior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig3.jpeg" height="612" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Axial <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram shows the thebesian valve (arrow) at the junction of the coronary sinus <i>(CS)</i> and right atrium <i>(RA)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig4.jpeg" height="759" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Four-chamber <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated coronary CT angiogram shows the fossa ovalis (arrow), a circular indentation in the middle of the interatrial septum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig5.jpeg" height="911" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Axial <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated coronary CT angiogram shows the triangular right atrial appendage (arrow), which extends superiorly from the right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig6a.jpeg" height="899" width="724" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 71-year-old woman who presented with shortness of breath and arrhythmia and received a diagnosis of cor triatriatum dexter. Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram <b>(b)</b> show a membrane (arrow) dividing the right atrium (<i>RA</i>). Note that there does not appear to be mixing of contrast material directly across the membrane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig6b.jpeg" height="899" width="751" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 71-year-old woman who presented with shortness of breath and arrhythmia and received a diagnosis of cor triatriatum dexter. Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram <b>(b)</b> show a membrane (arrow) dividing the right atrium (<i>RA</i>). Note that there does not appear to be mixing of contrast material directly across the membrane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig7a.jpeg" height="785" width="780" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 52-year-old man with a history of Ebstein anomaly who presented with worsening shortness of breath. <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. Long-axis vertical <b>(a)</b> and horizontal <b>(b</b>) steady-state free precession MR images show enlargement of the right side of the heart, ballooning of the anterior (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) and posterior (arrow in <b>a</b>) leaflets, and apical displacement of the septal leaflet (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig7b.jpeg" height="785" width="695" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 52-year-old man with a history of Ebstein anomaly who presented with worsening shortness of breath. <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. Long-axis vertical <b>(a)</b> and horizontal <b>(b)</b> steady-state free precession MR images show enlargement of the right side of the heart, ballooning of the anterior (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) and posterior (arrow in <b>a</b>) leaflets, and apical displacement of the septal leaflet (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig8.jpeg" height="599" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram in a 77-year-old man with a known history of tricuspid regurgitation who presented with worsening shortness of breath. Coronal multiplanar reformatted CT image obtained through the tricuspid valve in end systole shows incomplete coaptation of the tricuspid valve (arrow). Note the enlarged right atrium <i>(RA)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig9a.jpeg" height="779" width="629" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 76-year-old woman with a history of tricuspid regurgitation who presented with shortness of breath. <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Axial steady-state free precession MR image obtained in systole shows right atrial enlargement and two dephasing jets (arrows) into the right atrium that resulted from turbulent regurgitant flow. Note the heterogeneous signal intensity in the right atrium, a finding consistent with turbulent flow. <b>(b)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram obtained in systole shows right atrial enlargement and high-velocity turbulent flow in the right atrium, as indicated by aliasing artifact (arrows). (<a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a> can be used as a reference for a normal right atrial size at echocardiography.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig9b.jpeg" height="779" width="697" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 76-year-old woman with a history of tricuspid regurgitation who presented with shortness of breath. <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Axial steady-state free precession MR image obtained in systole shows right atrial enlargement and two dephasing jets (arrows) into the right atrium that resulted from turbulent regurgitant flow. Note the heterogeneous signal intensity in the right atrium, a finding consistent with turbulent flow. <b>(b)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram obtained in systole shows right atrial enlargement and high-velocity turbulent flow in the right atrium, as indicated by aliasing artifact (arrows). (<a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a> can be used as a reference for a normal right atrial size at echocardiography.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig10.jpeg" height="801" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 54-year-old woman with a remote history of right atrial radiofrequency ablation for arrhythmia who presented with dyspnea during exertion. Four-chamber reformatted <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated coronary CT angiogram shows what was initially thought to be a large right atrial aneurysm (arrow) compressing the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>. Surgical resection with pathologic confirmation revealed this to be a pseudoaneurysm. The cause was speculated to be iatrogenic, related to the remote radiofrequency ablation. Note the prominent crista terminalis. <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig11.jpeg" height="657" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> Axial <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram in a 38-year-old man who was referred for further evaluation after an enlarged pulmonary artery was seen at chest radiography. A large defect shown at the site of the foramen ovale (arrow) is consistent with an ostium secundum–type atrial septal defect. Note the large direct communication between the atria. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig12.jpeg" height="953" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram shows an ostium primum–type atrial septal defect at the atrioventricular canal (arrow). Note the mildly enlarged right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. (<a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a> can be used as a reference for a normal right atrial size at echocardiography.) <i>LA</i> = left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig13.jpeg" height="520" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Superior, or usual, type of sinus venosus atrial septal defect in a 65-year-old woman who was referred for preoperative evaluation. Axial oblique reformatted <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram shows an atrial septal defect (arrow) and anomalous drainage of the right superior pulmonary vein to the superior cavoatrial junction (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig14.jpeg" height="671" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Inferior type of sinus venosus atrial septal defect in a 67-year-old man who was referred for preoperative evaluation. Axial oblique <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram shows a low atrial septal defect (arrow) and anomalous drainage of the right inferior pulmonary artery to the inferior caval–atrial junction (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig15.jpeg" height="748" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Unroofed coronary sinus without a persistent left superior vena cava (type II) in a 34-year-old woman who was referred for preoperative evaluation. Multiplanar reformatted <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram shows complete unroofing of the coronary sinus <i>(CS)</i>, with involvement of the interatrial septum (arrow). This has created a single chamber contiguous with the right atrium <i>(RA),</i> left atrium <i>(LA),</i> and coronary sinus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig16a.jpeg" height="762" width="740" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 56-year-old man with arrhythmia. <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber Doppler transthoracic echocardiogram obtained in diastole shows right atrial enlargement and aliasing in the right ventricle (arrow) from high-velocity flow across the tricuspid valve. (<a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a> can be used as a reference for a normal right atrial size at echocardiography.) The maximum transvalvular gradient was 11 mm Hg. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated coronary CT angiogram shows right atrial enlargement and calcification and thickening of the tricuspid leaflets (arrow) resulting in incomplete opening in diastole, likely related to the patient’s remote history of endocarditis. The findings are consistent with tricuspid stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig16b.jpeg" height="762" width="733" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 56-year-old man with arrhythmia. <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber Doppler transthoracic echocardiogram obtained in diastole shows right atrial enlargement and aliasing in the right ventricle (arrow) from high-velocity flow across the tricuspid valve. (<a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a> can be used as a reference for a normal right atrial size at echocardiography.) The maximum transvalvular gradient was 11 mm Hg. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated coronary CT angiogram shows right atrial enlargement and calcification and thickening of the tricuspid leaflets (arrow) resulting in incomplete opening in diastole, likely related to the patient’s remote history of endocarditis. The findings are consistent with tricuspid stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig17a.jpeg" height="790" width="747" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 59-year-old man with a history of adriamycin-induced cardiomyopathy after treatment of lymphoma and subsequent diagnosis of constrictive pericarditis. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram shows a hyperechoic lesion in the left atrioventricular groove (arrow), biatrial enlargement, and tubular ventricles. (<a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a> can be used as a reference for a normal right atrial size at echocardiography.) <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram shows the hyperechoic lesion in the left atrioventricular groove to be a pericardial calcification, a finding also seen in the right atrioventricular groove (arrows). Biatrial enlargement and tubular ventricles are seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig17b.jpeg" height="790" width="728" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 59-year-old man with a history of adriamycin-induced cardiomyopathy after treatment of lymphoma and subsequent diagnosis of constrictive pericarditis. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram shows a hyperechoic lesion in the left atrioventricular groove (arrow), biatrial enlargement, and tubular ventricles. (<a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a> can be used as a reference for a normal right atrial size at echocardiography.) <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber reformatted <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram shows the hyperechoic lesion in the left atrioventricular groove to be a pericardial calcification, a finding also seen in the right atrioventricular groove (arrows). Biatrial enlargement and tubular ventricles are seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig18a.jpeg" height="682" width="671" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 19-year-old woman who was referred for workup of a questionable right atrial mass on the basis of CT findings. <b>(a)</b> Axial nongated contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest shows a possible mass in the atrium (circle). <b>(b)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram does not show a mass in the right atrium. The CT findings were attributed to mixing artifact from unopacified blood from the inferior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig18b.jpeg" height="682" width="654" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 19-year-old woman who was referred for workup of a questionable right atrial mass on the basis of CT findings. <b>(a)</b> Axial nongated contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest shows a possible mass in the atrium (circle). <b>(b)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram does not show a mass in the right atrium. The CT findings were attributed to mixing artifact from unopacified blood from the inferior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig19a.jpeg" height="562" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Multiple right atrial and tricuspid thrombi in a 22-year-old woman with a history of tricuspid valve replacement. <b>(a)</b> Coned-down view from right ventricular outflow tract transthoracic echocardiography shows multiple hyperechoic masses on the tricuspid valve (arrowheads) and in the right atrium (<i>RA;</i> arrow). <i>LVOT</i> = left ventricular outflow tract, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Axial nongated contrast-enhanced CT image through the heart shows multiple masses (arrows) on the tricuspid valve, interatrial septum, and lateral right atrial wall. Note the beam-hardening artifact from the tricuspid valve prosthesis (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows no enhancement of the right atrial (arrows) and tricuspid valve (arrowheads) masses, a finding consistent with thrombi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig19b.jpeg" height="546" width="705" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Multiple right atrial and tricuspid thrombi in a 22-year-old woman with a history of tricuspid valve replacement. <b>(a)</b> Coned-down view from right ventricular outflow tract transthoracic echocardiography shows multiple hyperechoic masses on the tricuspid valve (arrowheads) and in the right atrium (<i>RA;</i> arrow). <i>LVOT</i> = left ventricular outflow tract, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Axial nongated contrast-enhanced CT image through the heart shows multiple masses (arrows) on the tricuspid valve, interatrial septum, and lateral right atrial wall. Note the beam-hardening artifact from the tricuspid valve prosthesis (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows no enhancement of the right atrial (arrows) and tricuspid valve (arrowheads) masses, a finding consistent with thrombi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig19c.jpeg" height="546" width="772" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span> Multiple right atrial and tricuspid thrombi in a 22-year-old woman with a history of tricuspid valve replacement. <b>(a)</b> Coned-down view from right ventricular outflow tract transthoracic echocardiography shows multiple hyperechoic masses on the tricuspid valve (arrowheads) and in the right atrium (<i>RA;</i> arrow). <i>LVOT</i> = left ventricular outflow tract, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Axial nongated contrast-enhanced CT image through the heart shows multiple masses (arrows) on the tricuspid valve, interatrial septum, and lateral right atrial wall. Note the beam-hardening artifact from the tricuspid valve prosthesis (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows no enhancement of the right atrial (arrows) and tricuspid valve (arrowheads) masses, a finding consistent with thrombi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig20a.jpeg" height="646" width="696" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 76-year-old woman who was referred for further evaluation of a possible right atrial mass. Note the sparing of the fossa ovalis seen on all images. <b>(a, b)</b> Subcostal long-axis transthoracic echocardiogram <b>(a)</b> and axial nongated nonenhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> show a dumbbell-shaped mass in the interatrial septum (arrow). The mass shows fat attenuation on the CT image. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial proton-density–weighted <b>(c)</b> and axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show dumbbell-shaped thickening of the interatrial septum and help confirm the presence of fat (arrow) by showing signal dropout on the fat-suppressed images. The findings are consistent with <abbr title="lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum">LHIAS</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig20b.jpeg" height="646" width="782" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 76-year-old woman who was referred for further evaluation of a possible right atrial mass. Note the sparing of the fossa ovalis seen on all images. <b>(a, b)</b> Subcostal long-axis transthoracic echocardiogram <b>(a)</b> and axial nongated nonenhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> show a dumbbell-shaped mass in the interatrial septum (arrow). The mass shows fat attenuation on the CT image. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial proton-density–weighted <b>(c)</b> and axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show dumbbell-shaped thickening of the interatrial septum and help confirm the presence of fat (arrow) by showing signal dropout on the fat-suppressed images. The findings are consistent with <abbr title="lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum">LHIAS</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig20c.jpeg" height="668" width="713" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 76-year-old woman who was referred for further evaluation of a possible right atrial mass. Note the sparing of the fossa ovalis seen on all images. <b>(a, b)</b> Subcostal long-axis transthoracic echocardiogram <b>(a)</b> and axial nongated nonenhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> show a dumbbell-shaped mass in the interatrial septum (arrow). The mass shows fat attenuation on the CT image. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial proton-density–weighted <b>(c)</b> and axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show dumbbell-shaped thickening of the interatrial septum and help confirm the presence of fat (arrow) by showing signal dropout on the fat-suppressed images. The findings are consistent with <abbr title="lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum">LHIAS</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig20d.jpeg" height="668" width="763" aria-labelledby="fig20d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20d</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 76-year-old woman who was referred for further evaluation of a possible right atrial mass. Note the sparing of the fossa ovalis seen on all images. <b>(a, b)</b> Subcostal long-axis transthoracic echocardiogram <b>(a)</b> and axial nongated nonenhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> show a dumbbell-shaped mass in the interatrial septum (arrow). The mass shows fat attenuation on the CT image. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial proton-density–weighted <b>(c)</b> and axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show dumbbell-shaped thickening of the interatrial septum and help confirm the presence of fat (arrow) by showing signal dropout on the fat-suppressed images. The findings are consistent with <abbr title="lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum">LHIAS</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig20d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig21a.jpeg" height="626" width="783" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 74-year-old man who was referred for further evaluation of an incidentally discovered right atrial mass at transthoracic echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a large hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Axial nongated contrast-enhanced CT image shows a primarily hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the right atrium, with scattered areas of hyperattenuation. <b>(c)</b> Axial four-chamber fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows T2 prolongation in the mass (arrow), a typical finding in myxoma. <b>(d)</b> Axial four-chamber contrast-enhanced MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the right atrial mass (arrow). The finding of internal enhancement was a key feature supporting the diagnosis of myxoma as opposed to thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig21b.jpeg" height="626" width="691" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 74-year-old man who was referred for further evaluation of an incidentally discovered right atrial mass at transthoracic echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a large hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Axial nongated contrast-enhanced CT image shows a primarily hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the right atrium, with scattered areas of hyperattenuation. <b>(c)</b> Axial four-chamber fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows T2 prolongation in the mass (arrow), a typical finding in myxoma. <b>(d)</b> Axial four-chamber contrast-enhanced MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the right atrial mass (arrow). The finding of internal enhancement was a key feature supporting the diagnosis of myxoma as opposed to thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig21c.jpeg" height="713" width="803" aria-labelledby="fig21c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21c</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 74-year-old man who was referred for further evaluation of an incidentally discovered right atrial mass at transthoracic echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a large hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Axial nongated contrast-enhanced CT image shows a primarily hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the right atrium, with scattered areas of hyperattenuation. <b>(c)</b> Axial four-chamber fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows T2 prolongation in the mass (arrow), a typical finding in myxoma. <b>(d)</b> Axial four-chamber contrast-enhanced MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the right atrial mass (arrow). The finding of internal enhancement was a key feature supporting the diagnosis of myxoma as opposed to thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig21c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig21d.jpeg" height="713" width="670" aria-labelledby="fig21d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21d</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 74-year-old man who was referred for further evaluation of an incidentally discovered right atrial mass at transthoracic echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a large hyperechoic mass (arrow) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Axial nongated contrast-enhanced CT image shows a primarily hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the right atrium, with scattered areas of hyperattenuation. <b>(c)</b> Axial four-chamber fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows T2 prolongation in the mass (arrow), a typical finding in myxoma. <b>(d)</b> Axial four-chamber contrast-enhanced MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the right atrial mass (arrow). The finding of internal enhancement was a key feature supporting the diagnosis of myxoma as opposed to thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig21d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig22a.jpeg" height="719" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 57-year-old man who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram shows thickening of the pericardial space over the right ventricle, with a thin hyperechoic septation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram through the heart shows a soft-tissue mass invading the right ventricle and right atrium (arrows), as well as circumferential pericardial thickening. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the mass, which invades the right atrium, right ventricle, and pericardium (arrows). Biopsy revealed a granulocytic sarcoma (also referred to as a chloroma, myeloid sarcoma, or extramedullary myeloid tumor).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig22b.jpeg" height="592" width="682" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 57-year-old man who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram shows thickening of the pericardial space over the right ventricle, with a thin hyperechoic septation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram through the heart shows a soft-tissue mass invading the right ventricle and right atrium (arrows), as well as circumferential pericardial thickening. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the mass, which invades the right atrium, right ventricle, and pericardium (arrows). Biopsy revealed a granulocytic sarcoma (also referred to as a chloroma, myeloid sarcoma, or extramedullary myeloid tumor).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig22c.jpeg" height="592" width="644" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 57-year-old man who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Apical four-chamber transthoracic echocardiogram shows thickening of the pericardial space over the right ventricle, with a thin hyperechoic septation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated CT angiogram through the heart shows a soft-tissue mass invading the right ventricle and right atrium (arrows), as well as circumferential pericardial thickening. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the mass, which invades the right atrium, right ventricle, and pericardium (arrows). Biopsy revealed a granulocytic sarcoma (also referred to as a chloroma, myeloid sarcoma, or extramedullary myeloid tumor).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig23a.jpeg" height="647" width="608" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 74-year-old woman who was referred for further evaluation of a right atrial mass seen at transthoracic echocardiography after she presented with progressive shortness of breath. <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(a)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a hyperechoic lobulated mass (arrows) contiguous with the inferior vena cava and projecting into the right atrium. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Oblique coronal <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated chest CT angiogram shows a mass (arrow) projecting into the right atrium from the inferior vena cava, with a prominent vessel coursing through it. Abdominal imaging confirmed that the mass was contiguous with a hypervascular liver mass (not shown). The patient was found to have diffusely metastatic hepatocellular carcinoma, with direct tumor extension into the right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130010/asset/images/large/rg.351130010.fig23b.jpeg" height="647" width="720" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> Cardiac imaging findings in a 74-year-old woman who was referred for further evaluation of a right atrial mass seen at transthoracic echocardiography after she presented with progressive shortness of breath. <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(a)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a hyperechoic lobulated mass (arrows) contiguous with the inferior vena cava and projecting into the right atrium. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b)</b> Oblique coronal <abbr title="electrocardiographically">ECG</abbr>-gated chest CT angiogram shows a mass (arrow) projecting into the right atrium from the inferior vena cava, with a prominent vessel coursing through it. Abdominal imaging confirmed that the mass was contiguous with a hypervascular liver mass (not shown). The patient was found to have diffusely metastatic hepatocellular carcinoma, with direct tumor extension into the right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130010&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Akcay M, Bilen ES, Bilge M, Durmaz T, Kurt M. Prominent crista terminalis: as an anatomic structure leading to atrial arrhythmias and mimicking right atrial mass. <em>J Am Soc Echocardiogr</em> 2007;20(2):e9–e10. doi:10.1016/j.echo.2006.08.037. Published February 2007. Accessed April 24, 2013.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.echo.2006.08.037">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17275709/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Prominent+crista+terminalis%3A+as+an+anatomic+structure+leading+to+atrial+arrhythmias+and+mimicking+right+atrial+mass&amp;author=M+Akcay&amp;author=ES+Bilen&amp;author=M+Bilge&amp;author=T+Durmaz&amp;author=M+Kurt&amp;publication_year=2007&amp;journal=J+Am+Soc+Echocardiogr&amp;pages=e9-e10&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.echo.2006.08.037&amp;pmid=17275709">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Malouf JF, Edwards WD, Tajik AJ, Seward JB. Functional anatomy of the heart. In: Fuste